metadata.name: Richter #257
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse‚Ä¶ which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it‚Äôs about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

metadata.name: Memory #60
metadata.description:
"Memory" is an experiment in the dynamic interplay of soulful colors and forms. 
It is an exploration of smooth animation blending interesting fluid shapes. 
The piece is a continuous flow of forms and hues that seamlessly transition. 
The viewer can interactively zoom in and out and navigate to explore the full space of the artwork.
Furthermore the aspect ratio can be change to vary the framing of the piece, generating new impressions.
This invites the viewer to fully immerse themselves in the piece and experience it from different perspectives.
The name "Memory" reflects the intention to display an abstract representation of memories of a machine.
The colors aim to evoke a sense of emotion and depth. 

I created this work using twgl.js on a single fragment shader, my recent technique of choice. 

I hope you enjoy interacting with "Memory" and exploring the different aspects of the piece.

This piece uses webgl, it can thus only be viewed on browsers implementing webgl.

License: CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0
Dependencies: 
- twgljs - A Tiny WebGL helper Library (MIT license)
- psrdnoise.glsl (MIT license)
- isMobile (Unlicense)
For more information, view the license file

Interactions
'-' to zoom in. 
'+' to zoom out.
'f' to change the aspect ratio to fullscreen.
'1' to change the aspect ratio to square.
'a' to change the aspect ratio to portrait format.
'w' to change the aspect ratio to 16:9.
's' to save an image of the canvas.
't' to toggle the time (day/night) in the image.
'b' to toggle the frame.
'h' to increase the quality modifier (maximum is 3).
'l' to decrease the quality modifier (minimum is 1).
The quality modifier is a modifier on the width and height of the canvas.
Changing the modifier can affect the look of the image due to subpixel artifacts.
The modifier can be used to save higher resolution images.
Higher values of the modifier increase memory usage and can cause a browser or webgl instance to crash.
'arrow_up' to move up in the image.
'arrow_down' to move down in the image.
'arrow_right' to move right in the image.
'arrow_left' to move left in the image.

Francesco Forcellini, November 2022, Milano, Italy.
Compositions of spheres made with grids, proportions, symmetries and  broken symmetries,  order and casualties.

To save a Hi-Resolution image 6000px x 8000px press H and wait, the page will reload and start to render.

metadata.name: inlim:in #225
metadata.description:
"inlim:in" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel

Atemporal iridescent fragments of the in between. The series is inspired by the many liminal spaces and unseen influences that permeate the visible universe and its participants. Created with GLSL, every piece of the series is generated using the space around the visible object to cast its shape. The series creates a gentle and colorful expanse through which viewers might contemplate what it is to exist at an infinite threshold.

metadata.name: SURFERS #14
metadata.description:
Subscription token for 12 issues of The Tickle - weekly magazine for contemporary digital art and creative writing (@inwarhol), with this special limited edition created by itsgalo (@galoandstuff) titled "SURFERS".

Collect this token, and receive 12 issues - each issue is airdropped to your wallet every Friday!
Holders become members of The Tickle Subscribers Club, gaining access to exclusive airdrops of free art from our featured artists!

Collect multiple tokens to increase your subscription beyond 12 weeks!

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

SURFERS is a generative animated painting made from pixel array computations and modulo functions. It is an exploration of various dithering effects and the rhythmic qualities of pixel transformations.

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save an animated GIF.
Made with P5.js and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: Celebrations #38
metadata.description:
Celebration is a presentation of colors, patterns, and flow fields into a beautiful arrangement. The algorithm's core consists of a flow field packed with circles on top without collisions between themselves and the edges. Patterns are then drawn on top of the circles using Sayama's p5.pattern library.  I hope we take this holiday season to celebrate our little wins and successes with gratitude and enjoy what we have.

For flow field lovers, check out my study on flow fields at http://www.theflo.xyz/

metadata.name: BWEEPS  #96
metadata.description:
A minimalist, black-and-white generative profile picture (PFP) created to commemorate one-year anniversary of Bwople project by Gengoya. The artwork is derived from an initial sketch of Bwople which, despite being not the one that was chosen, still managed to captivate interests. The project provides a unique glimpse into an alternate universe in which Bwople could have been represented.

All images are hand-drawn work by Gengoya and composed by Vector Recite using PureSpider's fxhash-pfp maker tool.

To download the full size image on fx(hash):
- Click "open" below the image
- Left click on the image, a "Download image" button will appear on the bottom right.
- Click the "Download image" button.
